│ "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation replaces a select fed   │
│ by an fcmp with a minnum intrinsic when the select has nnan/ninf/nsz     │
│ FMF. This changes the result for the input +0.0 to -0.0, which is        │
│ observable in Alive2 as a mismatch. The original select preserves the    │
│ operand value (+0.0), while minnum may canonicalize to -0.0 under        │
│ certain FP semantics. Using nsz alone to justify this canonicalization   │
│ is too aggressive because it allows changing the sign-bit of zero in a   │
│ way that can be observable by users outside of operations that           │
│ explicitly ignore zero sign.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe first       │
│ transformation is in visitSelectInst: the select of two FP values under  │
│ nnan/ninf/nsz FMF is canonicalized to llvm.minnum.f16. The log shows:    │
│ \"IC: Replacing ... with call nnan ninf nsz @llvm.minnum.f16\". Alive    │
│ demonstrates that for %x = +0.0, the source produces +0.0 while the      │
│ transformed target yields -0.0. This indicates the canonicalization to   │
│ minnum is responsible for altering the sign of zero.\n\n3. Root Cause    │
│ Analysis:\nThe code currently allows canonicalizing to minnum/maxnum if  │
│ the select has NoNaNs and either:\n- hasNoSignedZeros(), or\n-           │
│ hasOneUse() and canIgnoreSignBitOfZero on the sole use.\nThis means that │
│ hasNoSignedZeros alone triggers the transformation without verifying     │
│ that users truly ignore zero sign. However, nsz on the select does not   │
│ grant permission to produce a different signed-zero value in a way that  │
│ could be observed by non-arithmetic consumers (e.g., another select,     │
│ bitcasts, stores, etc.). In this case, the converted minnum produced     │
│ -0.0 when the original select would yield +0.0, violating the original   │
│ semantics as seen by Alive2.\nTherefore, relying solely on               │
│ hasNoSignedZeros is insufficient for this min/max canonicalization, and  │
│ we must ensure that the result's sign-of-zero is not observable by its   │
│ uses. The existing secondary condition (hasOneUse &&                     │
│ canIgnoreSignBitOfZero) is the appropriate safety check.\n\n4. Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s):\nEdit file                                                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp, lines 3925-3956,  │
│ where the minnum/maxnum canonicalization condition is:\n\n    if         │
│ (SIFPOp->hasNoNaNs() &&\n        (SIFPOp->hasNoSignedZeros() ||\n        │
│ (SIFPOp->hasOneUse() &&\n                                                │
│ canIgnoreSignBitOfZero(*SIFPOp->use_begin())))) {\n      ... match       │
│ m_OrdOrUnordFMax/min and build maxnum/minnum ...\n    }\n\nChange the    │
│ condition to remove the hasNoSignedZeros() short-circuit and rely solely │
│ on the use-based check:\n\n    if (SIFPOp->hasNoNaNs() &&\n              │
│ (SIFPOp->hasOneUse() &&\n                                                │
│ canIgnoreSignBitOfZero(*SIFPOp->use_begin()))) {\n      ...\n            │
│ }\n\nThis ensures we only canonicalize to minnum/maxnum when the single  │
│ user ignores the sign bit of zero, preventing creation of -0.0 where     │
│ +0.0 would have been preserved.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy tightening the     │
│ condition for the minnum/maxnum canonicalization to require the          │
│ use-based canIgnoreSignBitOfZero check (and removing the                 │
│ hasNoSignedZeros short-circuit), we prevent incorrect transformations    │
│ that can change +0.0 to -0.0. This fixes the observed mismatch in the    │
│ reproducer while still allowing safe canonicalization when the sign of   │
│ zero is truly unobservable."})                                           │
